How do you troubleshoot unhealthy Kubernetes nodes?

Step 1 — Identify the problem node

kubectl get nodes

NAME          STATUS     ROLES    AGE
node-1        Ready      worker   10d
node-2        NotReady   worker   10d   ← problem
node-3        Ready      worker   10d

Step 2 — Describe the node

kubectl describe node node-2

Look at:

Conditions:
  Type              Status
  MemoryPressure    False     ← OK
  DiskPressure      True      ← PROBLEM — disk full
  PIDPressure       False     ← OK
  Ready             False     ← node unhealthy

Step 3 — Check node conditions meaning

Condition                | Status | Meaning
-------------------------|--------|-------------------------
Ready=False              | Bad    | kubelet not working
MemoryPressure=True      | Bad    | Node RAM full
DiskPressure=True        | Bad    | Disk full
PIDPressure=True         | Bad    | Too many processes
NetworkUnavailable=True  | Bad    | CNI issue (vpc-cni)

Step 4 — SSH into node and check

# SSH into EC2 node
ssh -i key.pem ec2-user@<node-ip>

# Check kubelet status
systemctl status kubelet

# Check kubelet logs
journalctl -u kubelet -f --since "30 min ago"

# Check disk
df -h

# Check memory
free -m

# Check CPU
top

Step 5 — Common fixes

Problem            | Fix
-------------------|---------------------------------------------------------
kubelet stopped    | systemctl restart kubelet
Disk full          | Delete unused images: docker system prune -a
Memory pressure    | Evict/move pods off node
Node unreachable   | Check EC2 instance state in AWS Console
CNI issue          | Restart aws-node pod on that node

Step 6 — Check pods on that node

# See all pods on problem node
kubectl get pods --all-namespaces \
  --field-selector spec.nodeName=node-2

Step 7 — Cordon + Drain (if node needs maintenance)

# Stop new pods scheduling on this node
kubectl cordon node-2

# Evict existing pods gracefully
kubectl drain node-2 --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data

# After fix — bring node back
kubectl uncordon node-2

In your stack (Karpenter)
With Karpenter, unhealthy nodes are often auto-replaced:

Node goes NotReady
        ↓
Karpenter detects unhealthy node
        ↓
Terminates it → provisions new node automatically

But you still check logs to find why it went unhealthy.
